Benue State government has confirmed one case of Lassa fever in the state. Commissioner for Health and Human Services, Dr Sunday Ongbabo in an interview with our correspondent explained that the suspected case of Lassa fever has undergone all the laboratory investigation and the result was positive. He said that the victim had been quarantined and is being treated, adding that the ministry had taken necessary measures to avoid the spread of the disease. Ongbabo also disclosed that government has set up an Emergency Operations Centre for the treatment of suspected cases of Lassa fever and other potential epidemics. He added that the Emergency Operations Centre which is established in conjunction with the Centre for Disease Control (CDC) is expected to carry out surveillance on all kinds of potential epidemics. Also speaking, an Epidemiologists, Dr Sam Ngishe said, they are carefully following contact list of persons who were suspected to have come in contact with  the said victim. According to him, a lot of awareness  creation, campaigns and the training of health care givers on early detection of infection, prevention, management and control of the disease is currently going on. In an interview with our correspondent, the chairman, Medical Advisory Committee of the medical facility where the victim is currently receiving treatment, Prof. Olusayo Alao, who also confirmed that a 40-year-old woman has so far tested positive of the disease, identified lack of water and constant power outage as some of the challenges hindering effective care for the victim. “We need a dedicated power back up especially in the Isolation Ward because if there is no water and power in this ward it will make the staff scared, because how will one go there in the night, the victim herself need to be constantly using running water,” he noted.